                - link "World Heritage Site" [ref=e366] [cursor=pointer]:

                - text: by
                - link "UNESCO" [ref=e367] [cursor=pointer]:

                - text: in 1983. It received more than 1.5 million visitors annually as of 2024, making it Peru's most visited tourist attraction. This photograph of Machu Picchu was taken in 1912 by
                - link "Hiram Bingham III" [ref=e368] [cursor=pointer]:

                - link "Eastern Cordillera" [ref=e362] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/Cordillera_Oriental_(Peru)
                - text: of southern Peru, about 2,430 metres (7,970 ft) above sea level. Often referred to as the "Lost City of the Incas", it was built around 1450, likely as an estate for the Inca emperor
                - link "Pachacuti" [ref=e363] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/Pachacuti
                - text: ", and was abandoned roughly a century later. Notable structures include the Temple of the Sun, the Temple of the Three Windows, and"
                - link "Intihuatana" [ref=e364] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/Intihuatana,_Urubamba
                - text: ", a ritual stone. Machu Picchu was"
                - link "designated a historic sanctuary" [ref=e365] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/Historic_Sanctuary_of_Machu_Picchu
                - text: by Peru in 1981, and a
                - link "World Heritage Site" [ref=e366] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/World_Heritage_Site
                - text: by
                - link "UNESCO" [ref=e367] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/UNESCO
                - text: in 1983. It received more than 1.5 million visitors annually as of 2024, making it Peru's most visited tourist attraction. This photograph of Machu Picchu was taken in 1912 by
                - link "Hiram Bingham III" [ref=e368] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/Hiram_Bingham_III
                - text: ", the American explorer who rediscovered the citadel, and was published in the April 1913 edition of"
                - link "National Geographic" [ref=e370] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/National_Geographic
                - text: . The image was taken after early clearing work, and shows the agricultural terraces, the central urban complex, and the steep peak of
                - link "Huayna Picchu" [ref=e371] [cursor=pointer]:
                  - /url: /wiki/Huayna_Picchu
                - text: rising in the background.
